passages.text: August 29, 2025 02:57 PM GMT
Don't have a lot of time? Here are some brief thoughts on a few key cross- asset debates we've had with investors in August on our out- of- consensus calls.
1) Could the quality of US data be eroded? Budgetary dysfunction has strained US data quality
2) Have investors been hedging USD? Probably, but data are scarce
3) Are 'bad' US data good or bad for stocks here? Bullish
4) Is there a rotation into European assets from the US? Maybe, but foreign net buying of US assets has not stopped
5) Can the UST curve really steepen more here? Yes
Exhibit 1: Demand for US equities is resilient - in aggregate, including flows outside of mutual funds and ETFs, foreign investors are net buying US stocks
Source: US Treasury, Haver Analytics, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 2: Our multi-asset allocation views

A brief thoughts on some of the key debates we've had with investors over the last few weeks on our out- of- consensus calls.

Since 2000, continuing resolutions have become the norm in the federal budget (Exhibit 3 Exhibit 1), limiting resource allocation and weakening agencies' effectiveness. Evidence suggests that a federal hiring freeze and spending cuts are undermining CPI data quality - in April, the BLS announced reductions to its CPI sample coverage. We think the increase in data imputations and their declining quality (Exhibit 4) will amplify volatility in future CPI prints.
Exhibit 3: Percentage of days in fiscal year under continuing resolutions has risen
Source: Congressional Research Service, Peterson Institute, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 4: The share of lower- quality imputations has increased sharply
Source: BLS, Morgan Stanley Research

Post- April data from Danish pension funds and insurers show that USD hedge ratios rose earlier in the year and then stabilized between May and June. March 2025 data show that Japanese life insurers lowered FX hedge ratios, Finnish pension funds increased coverage ratios and Australian superannuation funds reduced FX hedges on equities. As of December 2024, Swedish pension funds' FX coverage remained below their historical average, while Swiss funds stayed close to theirs.
Exhibit 5: Danish investors' USD hedge ratios rose since March 2025 and stayed flat thereafter
Source: Danish National Bank, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 6: As of March 2025, Japan lifers' hedge ratios fell

Source: Sumitomo Life, Dai-ichi Holdings, Nippon Life Insurance Company, Sony Financial Group, Tokio Marine Holdings, Asahi Mutual Life Insurance Company, Japan Post Group, Meiji Yasuda, T&D Holdings, Fukoku Mutual Life Insurance Company, MS&D Insurance Group Holdings, Morgan Stanley Research

Weak US data are bullish for stocks right now, in our view. US equities priced a growth slowdown back in April that's only now showing in the lagging macro data. A measured deterioration from here would confirm the shift to an early- cycle backdrop - a favorable environment for stocks - and potentially increase the expected magnitude of Fed cuts. Leading indicators also suggest continued strength in earnings.
Exhibit 7: Trade policy and growth concerns peaked with vol back in April, which coincided with lows in the S&P
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 8: Our leading earnings model has turned constructive, which has historically been a positive signal for EPS growth

Source: FactSet, Haver Analytics, Morgan Stanley Research; Note: As of June 30, 2025 (inputs are lagged by 1-2 months). The non-PMI LEI is a top-down macro indicator that was built to triangulate our earnings forecasts using alternative sources. Inputs include PMI Fed economic activity, Creighton U. business confidence, Chicago Fed supplier deliveries, Atlanta Fed wage tracker (inverse signal), NFIB small bus. most important problem inflation (inverse signal), and Brave-Butters Kelley cycle component of monthly GDP. Weightings are fixed over time.

Flows to European equities ETFs and mutual funds have been on a tear while flows to US funds have fallen. Overall foreign buying, however, shows that demand for US stocks is resilient - in fact, extremely resilient. The story is similar in the fixed income space. While US fiscal concerns have fed a narrative of USD bonds becoming less attractive, European and Japanese investors are on net still buying USTs. We also see that flows to all bond funds have been declining, suggesting that the rotation has been cross- asset and not cross- region.
Exhibit 9: US equity funds have seen large outflows since Liberation Day while flows to European funds have climbed
Source: Lipper, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 10: But in aggregate, including flows outside of mutual funds and ETFs, foreign investors are net buying US stocks
Source: US Treasury, Haver Analytics, Morgan Stanley Research

Our US rates team sees scope for the market to price more downside risk to the eventual trough policy rate as dovish language during Jackson Hole means that the market will likely price in insurance cuts from the Fed. Or to put another way, investors may see two cuts as a floor, with the potential for more on further labor market weakness. We expect this to continue to exert steepening pressure on the shape of the yield curve, even if term premium remains stable.
Exhibit 11: Market-implied trough fed funds rate and US Treasury 10-year yield
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 12: UST 10Y term premium has remained range-bound and still below the Liberation Day peak
Source: Bloomberg, Federal Reserve, Morgan Stanley Research
